# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: batting-average-baseball
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:batting-average-baseball/16-inch-softball] The first set of rules was published in 1937 by the Amateur Softball Association, in the same manual as the rules for fastpitch softball.
[src:batting-average-baseball/16-inch-softball] Game play for 16-inch softball is mostly consistent with standard softball game play.
[src:batting-average-baseball/16-inch-softball] In contrast to standard, or 12-inch (30.48 cm) softball, it is played with a ball 16 inches (40.64 cm) in circumference.
[src:batting-average-baseball/16-inch-softball] It is common to see higher arched pitching, and balls/strikes are determined by where the ball lands and crosses the batter's body.
[src:batting-average-baseball/16-inch-softball] Leagues may form co-ed, all-male, or all-female teams.
[src:batting-average-baseball/16-inch-softball] Additionally, teams may choose competitive or recreational leagues.
[src:batting-average-baseball/16-inch-softball] There may be rule variations associated with the specific field or league of play.
[src:batting-average-baseball/16-inch-softball] When playing in a co-ed league, there may be other rules that relate to the male-to-female ratio of team members and batting order.
[src:batting-average-baseball/16-inch-softball] The National Softball Association (NSA) also has a published set of rules governing 16-inch softball play.
[src:batting-average-baseball/16-inch-softball] The earliest known softball game of any kind was played at the Farragut Boat Club in Chicago on Thanksgiving Day 1887.
[src:batting-average-baseball/16-inch-softball] The first softball was a wrapped up boxing glove and the bat was a broom.
[src:batting-average-baseball/16-inch-softball] Play was encouraged by a reporter, George Hancock, who had been looking on.
[src:batting-average-baseball/16-inch-softball] Harvard and Yale students played the game while waiting to hear the results of the annual Harvard-Yale football game.
[src:batting-average-baseball/16-inch-softball] Until the turn of the 20th century, ball sizes ranged from 12 to 17 inches in circumference.
[src:batting-average-baseball/16-inch-softball] The 16-inch softball was eventually adopted in Chicago, perhaps because it did not travel as far as the popular 12- or 14-inch balls.
[src:batting-average-baseball/16-inch-softball] This also may have allowed for play on smaller playgrounds or even indoors, accommodating the Chicago landscape and climate.
[src:batting-average-baseball/16-inch-softball] Another possible advantage of the 16-inch ball was that it allowed everyone to play barehanded, and gloves were a rare luxury as the Great Depression hit Chicago particularly hard.
[src:batting-average-baseball/16-inch-softball] After the first national championship held in 1933 at the Century of Progress World's Fair, the sport grew in popularity.
[src:batting-average-baseball/16-inch-softball] A professional league was formed that lasted through the 1950s.
[src:batting-average-baseball/16-inch-softball] Teams drew crowds of over 10,000 each night.
[src:batting-average-baseball/16-inch-softball] Leagues continue today but not at the same level of popularity.
[src:batting-average-baseball/16-inch-softball] There are co-ed recreational leagues, competitive leagues and even a league for Chicago Public School students.
[src:batting-average-baseball/16-inch-softball] Many local organizations host regular season play, typically weekly games, as well as their own playoff systems.
[src:batting-average-baseball/16-inch-softball] National organizations, such as the NSA, host a variety of tournaments.
[src:batting-average-baseball/16-inch-softball] By placing well in NSA tournaments, teams can qualify and compete for the 16-inch softball world series.
[src:batting-average-baseball/16-inch-softball] Because local leagues may have slight variations in rules, the NSA world series is played by its own set of world series rules.
[src:batting-average-baseball/16-inch-softball] One notable change is that Chicago area players, who typically are not allowed to wear gloves, may choose to wear gloves in world series games.
[src:batting-average-baseball/16-inch-softball] Games are played with a deBeer Clincher 16" ball and gloves are used.
[src:batting-average-baseball/16-inch-softball] In 1996 Al Maag and Tony Reibel established the 16" Softball Hall of Fame.
[src:batting-average-baseball/16-inch-softball] Since inception, the organization has held annual inductee dinners attended by over 600 guests.
[src:batting-average-baseball/16-inch-softball] There is a museum in Forest Park, Illinois, a suburb of Chicago.
[src:batting-average-baseball/16-inch-softball] 16inchsoftballhof.com The Chicago 16" Softball Hall of Fame is a registered 501(c) not-for-profit organization.
[src:batting-average-baseball/16-inch-softball] The game can be seen being played in multiple scenes in the 1986 film *About Last Night*, whose storyline was set in Chicago.
[src:batting-average-baseball/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The **1877 major league baseball season** was contested from April 30 through October 6, 1877, and saw the Boston Red Caps as the pennant winner of the second season of the National League.
[src:batting-average-baseball/1877-major-league-baseball-season] Over the off-season, in December 1876, two teams were formally kicked out of the league for failing to fulfill their schedules: New York Mutuals and Philadelphia Athletics, contracting the league from eight to six teams.
[src:batting-average-baseball/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The Hartford Dark Blue would relocate from Hartford, Connecticut to Brooklyn, New York, as the Brooklyn Hartfords.
[src:batting-average-baseball/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The 1877 schedule consisted of 60 games for all six teams of the National League.
[src:batting-average-baseball/1877-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 12 games against the other five teams in the league.
[src:batting-average-baseball/1877-major-league-baseball-season] This was the first season that the National League adopted the format.
[src:batting-average-baseball/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The format would last only through the following season.
[src:batting-average-baseball/1877-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 30 featuring a game between the Boston Red Caps and Brooklyn Hartfords.
[src:batting-average-baseball/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the season was on October 6, featuring four teams.
[src:batting-average-baseball/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The Brooklyn Hartfords hosted a neutral site game.
[src:batting-average-baseball/1877-major-league-baseball-season] Three tie games, which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind occurred throughout the season (though standings were determined by total wins, not winning percentage).
[src:batting-average-baseball/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The Brooklyn Hartfords had two tie games.
[src:batting-average-baseball/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The Boston Red Caps, Chicago White Stockings, Cincinnati Reds, and Louisville Grays had one tie game each.
[src:batting-average-baseball/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The Chicago White Stockings would play their final game at 23rd Street Grounds on October 6 against the Louisville Grays, moving to Lakefront Park for the start of the 1878 season.
[src:batting-average-baseball/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The Brooklyn Hartfords hosted a neutral site game against the Chicago White Stockings on their last home game of the season, September 22, at the site of the former National Association's New Haven Elm Citys, at the Howard Avenue Grounds in New Haven, Connecticut.
[src:batting-average-baseball/1887-major-league-baseball-season] The **1887 major league baseball season** began on April 16, 1887.
[src:batting-average-baseball/1887-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on October 10, with the Detroit Wolverines and the St.
[src:batting-average-baseball/1887-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Browns as regular season champions of the National League and American Association, respectively.
[src:batting-average-baseball/1887-major-league-baseball-season] The Louisville Colonels set a Major League record which still stands for the most base on balls for a team in a game, with 19 against the Cleveland Blues on 21 September.
[src:batting-average-baseball/1887-major-league-baseball-season] Over the offseason, the National League's Kansas City Cowboys folded, and saw them replaced by the American Association's Pittsburgh Alleghenys.
[src:batting-average-baseball/1887-major-league-baseball-season] In place of the Alleghenys leaving the AA for the NL, the Cleveland Blues were enfranchised.
[src:batting-average-baseball/1887-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Maroons relocated to Indianapolis, Indiana as the Indianapolis Hoosiers.
[src:batting-average-baseball/1887-major-league-baseball-season] On July 14, Chicago was to play an exhibition game against the Eastern League Newark team, who were set to play black players Moses Fleetwood Walker (who formerly played in the majors in 1884 three years prior) and George Stovey (who the New York Giants had their eyes on signing).
[src:batting-average-baseball/1887-major-league-baseball-season] With threats from Chicago to not play against Newark if Walker and Stovey played, they were substituted for the game.
[src:batting-average-baseball/1887-major-league-baseball-season] Between Chicago's financial threats to not play against teams with people of color and other minor league teams creating petitions to force teams to release players of color, Organized Baseball effectively set up the baseball color line.
[src:batting-average-baseball/1887-major-league-baseball-season] The color line would remain firm for 60 years until the Brooklyn Dodgers called up Jackie Robinson in 1947, breaking the color line.
[src:batting-average-baseball/1887-major-league-baseball-season] The process of integration would then last for another 12 years until 1959, when the last major league team, the Boston Red Sox integrated by calling up Pumpsie Green.
[src:batting-average-baseball/1887-major-league-baseball-season] The 1887 schedule consisted of 140 games for all American Association teams and 126 games for all National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:batting-average-baseball/1887-major-league-baseball-season] Each AA team was scheduled to play 20 games against the other seven teams, while each NL team was scheduled to play 18 games against the other seven teams.
[src:batting-average-baseball/1887-major-league-baseball-season] Both the AA's 140-game format and NL's 126-game format were continued from their implementation the previous season.
[src:batting-average-baseball/1887-major-league-baseball-season] The NL would adopt the AA's format the following season, and each league would use this 140-game format until 1892.
[src:batting-average-baseball/1887-major-league-baseball-season] American Association Opening Day took place on April 16 featuring all eight teams, while National League Opening Day took place on April 27, featuring four teams.
[src:batting-average-baseball/1887-major-league-baseball-season] The American Association would see its final day of the regular season on October 10 with four teams, while the National League would see its final day of the season on October 8, featuring all eight teams.
[src:batting-average-baseball/1887-major-league-baseball-season] The 1887 World's Championship Series took place between October 10 and October 26.
[src:batting-average-baseball/1887-major-league-baseball-season] The 1887 season saw many radical changes which affected the game, as well as unity on rules by the American Association and National League.
[src:batting-average-baseball/1887-major-league-baseball-season] Two teams played in two neutral site games in which they were treated as the home team.
[src:batting-average-baseball/1887-major-league-baseball-season] Meanwhile, blue laws restricted Sunday activities in several localities, causing several teams of the American Association (which was informally referred to as the "Beer & Whiskey League" due to its openness on alcohol, compared to the National League) to play at ballparks in a different locality.
[src:batting-average-baseball/1887-major-league-baseball-season] 30 tie games (14 in AA, 16 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:batting-average-baseball/1887-major-league-baseball-season] In 1887, bases on balls (walks) were counted as hits by the major leagues in existence at the time.
[src:batting-average-baseball/1887-major-league-baseball-season] This inflated batting averages, with 11 players batting .400 or better, and the experiment was abandoned the following season.
[src:batting-average-baseball/1887-major-league-baseball-season] Historical statistics for the season were later revised, such that "Bases on balls shall always be treated as neither a time at bat nor a hit for the batter." This results in ambiguity for some players' season and career hits totals, notably with Cap Anson.
[src:batting-average-baseball/1887-major-league-baseball-season] Anson was credited with a .421 average and the National League batting title in 1887; however, the recalculation of averages with walks excluded lowered his average to .347 and retroactively gave the batting title to Sam Thompson.
[src:batting-average-baseball/1887-major-league-baseball-season] The 1887 batting average and hits are included below, using contemporary data on Baseball Reference.
[src:batting-average-baseball/1887-major-league-baseball-season] The Cleveland Blues join the American Association and play at National League Park in Cleveland, Ohio.
[src:batting-average-baseball/1887-major-league-baseball-season] The first structure of the South End Grounds, home of the Boston Beaneaters, would see its last game on September 10, seeing a completely new structure built over the following offseason.
[src:batting-average-baseball/2018-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The **2018 Major League Baseball season** began on March 29.
[src:batting-average-baseball/2018-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The regular season ended on October 1, extended a day for tiebreaker games to decide the winners of the National League Central and National League West.
[src:batting-average-baseball/2018-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The World Series began on October 23, and ended on October 28 with the Boston Red Sox defeating the Los Angeles Dodgers in five games to win their ninth World Series championship.
[src:batting-average-baseball/2018-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The 89th Major League Baseball All-Star Game was held on July 17 at Nationals Park, the home of the Washington Nationals.
[src:batting-average-baseball/2018-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The American League won, 8–6, in 10 innings.
[src:batting-average-baseball/2018-major-league-baseball-season-p01] This was also the last season for August trade waivers.
[src:batting-average-baseball/2018-major-league-baseball-season-p01] As has been the case since 2013, all teams played their four division opponents 19 times each for a total of 76 games.
[src:batting-average-baseball/2018-major-league-baseball-season-p01] They played six or seven games against each of the other ten same-league opponents for a total of 66 games, and 20 interleague games.
[src:batting-average-baseball/2018-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The primary interleague match-ups were AL East vs NL East, AL Central vs NL Central, and AL West vs NL West.
[src:batting-average-baseball/2018-major-league-baseball-season-p01] Since "natural rivalry" matchups were part of the three-year divisional rotation, the schedule format for interleague games was different from previous years.
[src:batting-average-baseball/2018-major-league-baseball-season-p01] Under the new collective bargaining agreement reached in December 2016, the regular season was extended to 187 days in order to add four additional off-days for all teams.
[src:batting-average-baseball/2018-major-league-baseball-season-p01] All teams were scheduled to play Opening Day, March 29—the earliest domestic start of a regular season in league history until the 2019 season.
[src:batting-average-baseball/2018-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The Sunday night game before the All-Star Game was replaced by a single, nationally televised game on the Thursday after the All-Star Game (which for 2018, was played between the St.
[src:batting-average-baseball/2018-major-league-baseball-season-p01] Louis Cardinals and Chicago Cubs), before all other teams returned from break the next day.
[src:batting-average-baseball/2018-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The Minnesota Twins and the Cleveland Indians played a two-game series at Hiram Bithorn Stadium in San Juan, Puerto Rico, on April 17 and 18, while the Los Angeles Dodgers and San Diego Padres played a three-game series at Estadio de Béisbol Monterrey in Monterrey, Mexico, from May 4 to 6.
[src:batting-average-baseball/2018-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The 2018 MLB Little League Classic at BB&T Ballpark in Williamsport, Pennsylvania, coinciding with the Little League World Series, returned to the schedule.
[src:batting-average-baseball/2018-major-league-baseball-season-p01] It was played between the Philadelphia Phillies and the New York Mets on August 19.
[src:batting-average-baseball/2018-major-league-baseball-season-p01] Beginning in the 2018 season, MLB implemented new pace of play rules, which include limiting the number of mound visits for each team to six per nine innings.
[src:batting-average-baseball/2018-major-league-baseball-season-p01] Teams will receive an additional visit for every extra inning played.
[src:batting-average-baseball/2018-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The Detroit Tigers modified the Olde English 'D' on the home jersey to match the 'D' on the cap.
[src:batting-average-baseball/2018-major-league-baseball-season-p01] Other than a one-season hiatus of 'D' usage in 1960, this is the first major change to the Tigers' home jersey since 1934.
[src:batting-average-baseball/2018-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The Cleveland Indians have confirmed this will be the final season using the Chief Wahoo logo on its uniforms.
[src:batting-average-baseball/2018-major-league-baseball-season-p01] It will be replaced at the start of the 2019 season.
[src:batting-average-baseball/2018-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The team wore a Wahoo-less uniform through their September 6–9 series with the Blue Jays, as the team had been sued unsuccessfully by a group in Ontario in October 2016 to prevent the team from donning the logo during Toronto home games through the 2016 ALCS.
[src:batting-average-baseball/2018-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The Oakland Athletics added a kelly green alternate jersey to commemorate the franchise's 50th anniversary in Oakland.
[src:batting-average-baseball/2018-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The uniforms are used during every Friday home game.
[src:batting-average-baseball/2018-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The Washington Nationals added a second navy blue jersey to commemorate the team's hosting of the 2018 All-Star Game.
[src:batting-average-baseball/2018-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The uniform features the script "Nationals" in white with red trim and numerals in red with white trim.
[src:batting-average-baseball/2018-major-league-baseball-season-p01] Both the Cincinnati Reds and the Pittsburgh Pirates replaced their camouflage uniforms with new white alternate jerseys featuring olive and military green logos, letters and numbers.
[src:batting-average-baseball/2018-major-league-baseball-season-p01] As is the custom for the reigning World Series champions, the Astros wore gold-lettered uniforms at their home opener April 2 and 3.
[src:batting-average-baseball/2018-major-league-baseball-season-p01] 42 on April 15, the 71st anniversary of Jackie Robinson's debut in the majors.
[src:batting-average-baseball/2018-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The Orioles wore special caps and green uniforms on April 22, Earth Day.
[src:batting-average-baseball/2018-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The Reds and Diamondbacks wore Spanish language "Los Rojos" and "Los D-backs" uniforms May 5, Cinco de Mayo.
[src:batting-average-baseball/2018-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The Diamondbacks wore them again September 8.
[src:batting-average-baseball/2018-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The Royals wore an alternate uniform with a crown atop the R, and a cap with a crown instead of the "KC", on June 30 in Seattle.
[src:batting-average-baseball/2018-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The Blue Jays wore red uniforms on July 1, Canada Day.
[src:batting-average-baseball/2018-major-league-baseball-season-p01] They wore a cap with a gold maple leaf, as well.
[src:batting-average-baseball/2018-major-league-baseball-season-p01] All US-based teams wore Stars and Stripes caps and uniforms from July 2–4, ending with Independence Day.
[src:batting-average-baseball/2018-major-league-baseball-season-p01] Teams wore caps denoting what league they play for (there were nine interleague series during the time period).
[src:batting-average-baseball/2018-major-league-baseball-season-p01] For the second straight year, MLB sponsored Players Weekend, an event for which all teams wore special uniforms with design cues reminiscent of typical Little League uniforms.
[src:batting-average-baseball/2018-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The event was held August 24 to 26, again coinciding with the final weekend of the Little League World Series.
[src:batting-average-baseball/2018-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The Royals wore Spanish-language "Los Reales" uniforms September 1.
[src:batting-average-baseball/2018-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The Orioles wore Braille uniforms September 18 to mark the 40th anniversary of the National Federation of the Blind's headquarters moving to Baltimore.
[src:batting-average-baseball/2018-major-league-baseball-season-p01] They became the first pro sports team ever to wear such uniforms.
[src:batting-average-baseball/2018-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The uniforms had the name "Orioles" in Braille, and the players' last names were in Braille.
[src:batting-average-baseball/2018-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The Phillies will wear their 1980s powder blue uniforms for select Thursday home games.
[src:batting-average-baseball/2018-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The Athletics and White Sox wore 1968 throwbacks April 17 to mark the 50th anniversary of the Athletics' first season in Oakland.
[src:batting-average-baseball/2018-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The Tigers and Royals wore Negro leagues throwbacks May 6.
[src:batting-average-baseball/2018-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The Tigers wore the uniforms of the Detroit Stars, and the Royals wore the uniforms of the Kansas City Monarchs.
[src:batting-average-baseball/2018-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The Padres wore 1998 throwbacks May 12 to mark the 20th anniversary of their 1998 NL title.
[src:batting-average-baseball/2018-major-league-baseball-season-p01] They will wear them again at select Wednesday games.
[src:batting-average-baseball/2018-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The Royals wore 1969 throwbacks May 19 to mark the franchise's 50th season.
[src:batting-average-baseball/2018-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The uniforms also had the MLB 100th anniversary patch, which all teams wore that season.
[src:batting-average-baseball/2018-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The White Sox and Brewers wore 1980s throwbacks June 2 and 3.
[src:batting-average-baseball/2018-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The Marlins wore 1993 throwbacks June 8 to 10 to mark their 25th anniversary.
[src:batting-average-baseball/2018-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The Braves wore 1974 throwbacks June 22 and 23 to celebrate Hank Aaron Heritage Weekend.
[src:batting-average-baseball/2018-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The Mariners marked the 20th anniversary of their 1998 "Turn Ahead the Clock" promotion by wearing the uniforms from that game June 30 against Kansas City.
[src:batting-average-baseball/2018-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The Brewers and Pirates wore Negro league throwbacks July 13.
[src:batting-average-baseball/2018-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The Brewers wore the uniforms of the Milwaukee Bears, and the Pirates wore the uniforms of the Pittsburgh Crawfords.
[src:batting-average-baseball/2018-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The Brewers wore Milwaukee Bears uniforms August 2.
[src:batting-average-baseball/2018-major-league-baseball-season-p01] Their opponents, the Rockies, wore their regular uniforms.
[src:batting-average-baseball/2018-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The Mariners and Astros wore throwbacks on August 10; the Mariners wore their 1979 throwbacks, and the Astros wore their "Tequila Sunrise" uniforms.
[src:batting-average-baseball/2018-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The Angels wore California Angels throwbacks from 1976 to 1985 on August 27.
[src:batting-average-baseball/2018-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The Rays wore their 1998 inaugural throwbacks on March 31 against the Boston Red Sox, on June 9 against the Seattle Mariners, and on June 23 against the New York Yankees, along with September 8 against the Baltimore Orioles.
[src:batting-average-baseball/2018-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The Tigers wore their 1968 road uniforms September 8 at home to mark the 50th anniversary of their winning the 1968 World Series title.
[src:batting-average-baseball/2018-major-league-baseball-season-p02] This was the fifth year of the current eight-year deals with Fox Sports, ESPN and TBS.
[src:batting-average-baseball/2018-major-league-baseball-season-p02] Fox aired eight weeks of baseball on Saturday Nights leading up to the 2018 Major League Baseball All-Star Game which also aired on Fox.
[src:batting-average-baseball/2018-major-league-baseball-season-p02] Fox also televised Saturday afternoon games for the last four weeks of the regular season.
[src:batting-average-baseball/2018-major-league-baseball-season-p02] FS1 televised games on Tuesday and on Saturdays both during the afternoon and night.
[src:batting-average-baseball/2018-major-league-baseball-season-p02] ESPN televised games on its flagship telecast *Sunday Night Baseball* as well as Monday and Wednesday Nights.
[src:batting-average-baseball/2018-major-league-baseball-season-p02] TBS televised Sunday afternoon games for the last 13 weeks of the regular season.
[src:batting-average-baseball/2018-major-league-baseball-season-p02] Fox and ESPN Sunday Night Baseball telecasts were exclusive; all other national telecasts were subject to local blackout.
[src:batting-average-baseball/2018-major-league-baseball-season-p02] TBS televised the American League Wild Card Game, Division Series and televised the Championship Series.
[src:batting-average-baseball/2018-major-league-baseball-season-p02] ESPN televised the National League Wild Card, along with the National League West and Central tie-breaker games.
[src:batting-average-baseball/2018-major-league-baseball-season-p02] FS1 and MLB Network televised the National League Division Series.
[src:batting-average-baseball/2018-major-league-baseball-season-p02] Fox and FS1 televised the National League Championship Series.
[src:batting-average-baseball/2018-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The World Series aired exclusively on Fox for the 19th consecutive year.
[src:batting-average-baseball/2018-major-league-baseball-season-p02] Prior to the season, Major League Baseball reached an exclusive agreement with Facebook to stream 25-games for free on Facebook Watch.
[src:batting-average-baseball/2018-major-league-baseball-season-p02] Backup announcers Matt Shepard and Kirk Gibson replaced them for the rest of the season.
[src:batting-average-baseball/2018-major-league-baseball-season-p02] It was later announced that Impemba and Allen's contracts were not renewed for future seasons, ending their 17 years together as broadcast partners.
[src:batting-average-baseball/2018-major-league-baseball-season-p02] Nine regular season games were broadcast exclusively in the United States on Facebook Watch, beginning with the April 4 game between the New York Mets and Philadelphia Phillies.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] Dunn's statistical profile was highly unusual for its day; he walked, struck out, or homered in nearly half his career plate appearances.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] Consistent with the principles of the then-emerging sabermetric movement, Dunn helped prove that a batter could significantly contribute to his team despite an unimpressive batting average.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] Today, he is considered one of the better hitters of his era.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] However, his defense was panned by both traditional scouting methods and modern defensive metrics.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] Dunn was a dual-sport athlete at New Caney High School near Houston, Texas, playing both baseball and football.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] Although Dunn was naturally right-handed, his father Skip taught him to bat left-handed after noticing that he hit for greater power as a lefty.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] Growing up, he cheered for the hometown Houston Astros.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] After his graduation from high school, the Cincinnati Reds drafted Dunn in the second round (50th overall) of the 1998 Major League Baseball draft.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] New Caney retired Dunn's football and baseball numbers in 2015.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] It also named its baseball field after him.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] A standout football quarterback, Dunn went 24–9 in three seasons as a starter in high school and won the district championship in his senior season.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] Dunn was recruited by Notre Dame, Tennessee, and Texas A&M, but committed to the Texas Longhorns football team as part of Mack Brown's first recruiting class.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] He struck an agreement with the Cincinnati Reds which allowed him to play for the Longhorns during the college football season.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] However, Dunn never played a snap in a competitive game.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] Although he started the season as the No.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] 3 quarterback, he found himself backing up Major Applewhite after Richard Walton was injured.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] With Applewhite entrenched in the starting role for the foreseeable future and star recruit Chris Simms arriving on campus, Dunn was asked to move to the tight end position in spring 1999.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] He briefly practiced as a tight end, but ultimately left the Longhorns to concentrate on baseball.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] Dunn played four seasons in the minor leagues.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] Although he did not exhibit the drastically low batting averages of his major league career - he never batted lower than .281 - he showed strong plate discipline at an early age, and never posted an on-base percentage lower than .404.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] The Reds offered to promote Dunn straight from A-ball to the major leagues near the end of the 1999 season (*see Cup of coffee*), but Dunn declined the call-up, preferring to focus on refining his swing.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] Entering the 2001 season, Dunn was ranked highly by several Minor League Baseball analysts.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] 18 in the nation, and *Baseball America* ranked him at No.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] He was promoted to Double-A to start the season and dominated, hitting 12 home runs and drawing 24 walks in 39 games.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] He was quickly promoted to Triple-A, where he continued his hot streak, hitting 20 home runs and drawing 38 walks in 55 games.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] He was invited to the All-Star Futures Game, where he hit a 400-foot home run.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] The Reds called up Dunn to the majors on July 20, 2001.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] He promptly set a National League rookie record for the most home runs in a month by hitting 12 in August; the record stood for 16 years, until Cody Bellinger hit 13 home runs in June 2017.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] In his rookie season, Dunn played in 66 games, batting .262 with 19 home runs and 43 RBIs.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] Dunn received a single vote in 2001 National League Rookie of the Year voting, tying him for fourth place with Bud Smith.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] In 2002, Dunn hit .249 with 26 home runs and 76 RBIs as well as a career-high 128 walks and a .400 on-base percentage.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] At mid-season, Dunn was hitting .300 with 17 home runs and 54 RBIs, earning him a selection to the 2002 National League All-Star team.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] In that game, Dunn hit a ball to center field that was a few feet from being a game ending home run (the game famously ended in a tie).
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] He also walked in his only other plate appearance.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] Dunn's 2003 season was a steep decline from his previous All-Star campaign as he hit just .215 with 27 home runs and 57 RBIs.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] Along with his struggles at the plate, Dunn led all major league outfielders in errors, with 10, and suffered a thumb sprain while attempting a diving catch in mid-August that forced him to miss the remainder of the season.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] Dunn's most productive season came in 2004, when he posted career highs in batting average (.266), home runs (46), runs (105), hits (151), slugging percentage (.569), and on-base plus slugging (OPS) (.957).
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] On September 30, 2004, Dunn once again got his name in Major League Baseball's record book.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] That day, Dunn struck out three times against Chicago Cubs right-hander Mark Prior, raising his season total to 191 and surpassing Bobby Bonds' single season strikeout record of 189, set in 1970.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] He finished the season with 195 strikeouts and had a strikeout percentage of 34.3%, both of which led all of MLB.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] He held the record until Ryan Howard broke it on September 27, 2007.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] On August 10, 2004, Dunn hit the longest home run in the history of Great American Ball Park, a 535-foot blast to straightaway center that went over the batter's eye and bounced off Mehring Way into a section of the Ohio River that is considered part of Kentucky.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] As of June 2025, it is the fourth-longest home run in MLB history and the longest since 1971.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] Dunn's 46 home runs in 2004 were the fourth most in Cincinnati Reds history.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] That year, he joined Hall of Fame second baseman Joe Morgan as the only Reds players to score 100 runs, drive in 100 runs, and draw 100 walks in a single season.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] Dunn's 2005 season was similar to the previous year, with a slight dip in production as he hit .247 with 40 home runs and 101 RBIs while once again leading in strikeouts (168) and strikeout percentage (30.9%).
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] By reaching the 40 home run plateau for a second consecutive season, Dunn became the fourth player in Reds history to hit 40 home runs in multiple seasons.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] Prior to the start of the 2006 season, Dunn signed a 2-year, $18 million extension that bought out his final two years of arbitration, as well as a club option for a third year in 2008.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] Dunn once again hit 40 home runs, but once again saw a decrease in his average (.234) and RBIs (92).
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] For the third consecutive season, Dunn led all of MLB in strikeouts (194) and strikeout percentage (34.6%).
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] He also led all major league outfielders in errors, with 12, and had the lowest fielding percentage among left fielders, at .960.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] On June 30 of that season, Dunn made Cincinnati headlines with one of the biggest home runs of his career, a walk-off grand slam to cap a 9-run rally to beat the Indians, which kept the Reds tied atop the NL Central with St.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] During a lengthy rain delay on July 21, 2006, Dunn made a prank phone call from the clubhouse to Reds radio announcer Marty Brennaman.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] Brennaman was filling air time by taking calls from listeners, a segment he dubbed "The Banana Phone".
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] Dunn, who identified himself as "Adam from Milwaukee" and spoke in a goofy voice, asked Brennaman if he thought Reds' first baseman Scott Hatteberg was a good player, then asked if the announcer was wearing a shirt.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] The clip went viral, and is frequently replayed on Cincinnati radio.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] In a 2012 poll, Reds fans voted the segment their all-time favorite "off-beat Marty" call.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] 2007 was a return to form for Dunn as he hit .264 while reaching the 40 home run and 100 RBI plateaus again, becoming the first and only Red to hit 40 home runs in four consecutive seasons.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] On October 31, 2007, Dunn's $13 million option was picked up by the Reds, making him the highest-paid player on the team.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] Going into the final season under contract, Dunn hit .233 with 32 home runs and 74 RBIs, before being traded to Arizona.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] In his 8 seasons with Cincinnati, Dunn hit 270 home runs with 646 RBIs, 755 walks and 1,212 strikeouts, all of which were within the top ten in team history.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] In 2018, he was named to the Cincinnati Reds Hall of Fame.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] On August 11, 2008, Dunn was traded to the Arizona Diamondbacks for right-handed pitcher Dallas Buck and two other players to be named later.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] Within the next month, Arizona sent catcher Wilkin Castillo and pitcher Micah Owings to the Reds to complete the trade.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] In 2008, Dunn walked 19.1% of the time, the highest percentage in major league baseball; however, he also struck out 164 times in 651 plate appearances, a strikeout percentage of 31.7%.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] Defensively, he had the lowest fielding percentage of all starting major league left fielders, .968, and committed more errors (7) than any other NL left fielder.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] With Arizona in 2008, Dunn hit .243 with 8 home runs and 26 RBIs, while walking 42 times and striking out 44.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] Overall between Cincinnati and Arizona, Dunn hit .236, while once again reaching exactly 40 home runs and 100 RBIs.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] On February 11, 2009, Dunn agreed to a two-year, $20 million contract with the Washington Nationals.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] In his first game as a National, he hit a home run and had four RBIs.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] On July 4, 2009, he hit his 300th career home run.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] During the 2009 season, Dunn transitioned to first base.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] For the year, Dunn hit .267 with 38 home runs and 105 RBIs.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] On July 7, 2010, Dunn hit three home runs in a single game for the first time in his career as the Nationals beat the Padres 7–6.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] He hit a three-run homer and two solo homers to join Alfonso Soriano as the only Nationals players to accomplish the feat at the time.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] For the 2010 season, Dunn saw a slight decrease in productivity from 2009, as he hit .260 with 38 home runs and 103 RBIs, but his walk rate dropped from 17.4% to 11.9% while his strikeout rate climbed from 26.5% to 30.7%.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] On December 2, 2010, Dunn agreed to a four-year, $56 million deal with the Chicago White Sox.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] On April 6, 2011, Dunn underwent an appendectomy which caused him to miss five games.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] Prior to the appendectomy, Dunn was hitting .286 with a home run and 5 RBIs.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] However, after returning, Dunn struggled drastically, leading to reduced playing time as the year proceeded.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] He ended the season with a .159 average, .292 on-base percentage, .277 slugging percentage, .569 OPS, and 177 strikeouts, hitting only 11 home runs and recording 42 RBI, putting together by far the worst season of his career.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] The 177 strikeouts set a new White Sox team record for most strikeouts in a season by a batter, beating the previous record of 175 held by Dave Nicholson.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] Dunn's 2011 campaign was by far the worst of any player in the majors, as he batted .159 in 496 appearances at the plate.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] He fell six plate appearances short, however, in having the worst batting average to qualify for the batting title since Bill Bergen had hit .139 as a starter for the 1909 Brooklyn Superbas.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] Through 2011, he led all active left fielders in career errors, totaling 60 errors.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] Frustrated by his poor performance in 2011, Dunn pledged to change his offseason preparation so as to "not let this happen again." By the end of May 2012, Dunn surpassed his entire home run total from the year before and was leading the American League in walks.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] In 2012, Dunn struck out in 36 straight games, a record for a position player until 2017, when Yankees rookie Aaron Judge struck out in 37 straight games.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] On July 1, Dunn was elected by his peers to the 83rd All-Star Game in Kansas City, his second career All-Star selection and one of four White Sox selections on the season.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] On July 24, Dunn became the fourth left-handed White Sox player to hit 30 home runs in a season, joining Oscar Gamble, Robin Ventura and Jim Thome.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] He recorded his 1,000th RBI on August 13.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] In a game against the Kansas City Royals on August 18, Dunn hit his 35th home run of the season and 400th in his career when he connected on a two-run shot in the eighth inning, becoming the 50th MLB player to hit 400 career home runs.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] Dunn finished the 2012 season with a .204 batting average, 41 home runs, and 96 RBI.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] He also led the majors with walks (105) and strikeouts (222).
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] He became only the 3rd player to join the 200 strikeout club and his number of strikeouts established a new American League record, falling just one short of the major league record set by Mark Reynolds in 2009.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] On August 5, 2014, much to the delight of the remaining fans at U.S.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] Cellular Field and members of the White Sox dugout, Dunn pitched the top of the ninth inning during a demoralizing blowout loss of 16–0 to the Texas Rangers.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] Dunn's outing marked his first career pitching appearance and he didn't disappoint, as the power hitting DH landed his first pitch, a 78-mph fastball, for a called strike to Rangers shortstop Elvis Andrus.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] With Dunn taking the mound and Leury Garcia pitching earlier in the season on April 16, it marked the first time since 1979 that position players pitched in two games in the same season for the White Sox.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] The White Sox traded Dunn to the Oakland Athletics on August 31, 2014, in exchange for Nolan Sanburn.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] Hours after the trade was announced, Dunn announced he would "probably" retire after the 2014 season.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] On September 1, Dunn made his first plate appearance with Oakland and hit a two-run home run against the Seattle Mariners.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] He became the 12th player in Athletics history to hit a home run in his first at-bat with the organization.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] After a few productive games early on with the A's, Dunn's performance declined and became similar to his time with Chicago.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] In 25 games with Oakland, he batted .212 with a .316 on-base percentage, two home runs and 10 RBIs.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] Dunn is one of fourteen players to have played 2,000 games without making the postseason, as Dunn played in 2,001 games, which was the longest for any active player at the time of his retirement .
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] On the last day of the season, the Athletics clinched the second AL Wild Card spot, which meant he was on a postseason roster for the first (and last) time.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] However, he did not make an appearance in the AL Wild Card Game, which ended with a 9–8 loss to the Kansas City Royals.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] Dunn confirmed his retirement after the game.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] On March 1, 2009, Dunn joined the United States team for the 2009 World Baseball Classic at the late request of coach Davey Johnson.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] In a first-round game against Canada in Toronto on March 7, he hit a two-run home run and batted in a run on a sacrifice fly play.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] The next day, Dunn hit a long solo home run and scored on a three-run triple by Chris Iannetta in a blowout victory over Venezuela.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] During the tournament, Dunn tied for the team lead with 3 home runs, batting .304 with 9 walks and 10 strikeouts in 8 games.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] Dunn was selected to appear on the ballot for the 2020 Baseball Hall of Fame vote but was eliminated in his first year of eligibility.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] He was inducted into the Reds Hall of Fame in 2018.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] Dunn helped establish and manages Marucci Elite Texas, a traveling club team that competes in national club baseball competitions.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] Over the course of Dunn's career, FanGraphs calculated that he accumulated 240.1 offensive runs above average, which made him the 23rd-best offensive player in baseball for that period, between Hanley Ramirez and Gary Sheffield.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] Dunn was an effective batter, despite some shortcomings: he had trouble hitting to the opposite field, making him vulnerable to the infield shift, and he lacked the speed and athleticism to consistently leg out infield hits.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] He exhibited outstanding power and plate discipline.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] As of June 2025, his 15.8% walk rate is the 40th-highest of all time among qualified hitters, just ahead of Reds teammate Joey Votto, and his at bats per home run ratio of 14.90 is the 17th-highest of all time (11th at the time of his retirement).
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] Dunn's eight Opening Day home runs are the most of all time, tied with Frank Robinson and Ken Griffey Jr.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] However, Dunn's patience at the plate contributed to his high strikeout totals; he claimed that he tended to wait for the perfect pitch, and sometimes struck out looking as a result.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] Throughout his career, he was among the major league leaders in number of pitches per at-bat.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] As of June 2025, he is third on the all-time strikeout list, with 2,379 strikeouts, although this is partially a testament to his long career: his 28.6% strikeout rate is the 107th-highest of all time among qualified hitters.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] In addition, Dunn's 19 golden sombreros (4+ strikeouts in a single game) are fourth-most all-time, tied with Bo Jackson .
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] Dunn's 222 strikeouts in 2012 are the second-most strikeouts in a single season in MLB history (and the AL record), as of 2024.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] Dunn was only one strikeout behind Mark Reynolds' MLB record, despite finishing the season with 13 fewer plate appearances.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] Viewed in totality, Dunn was a prototypical "Three True Outcomes" hitter (that is, a player who frequently walks, strikes out, and hits home runs - in other words, a player whose batting outcomes are relatively unaffected by defensive luck).
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] For his career, Dunn walked, homered, or struck out in 49.9% of his plate appearances.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] At the time of his retirement, Dunn's TTO percentage was the highest figure in baseball history for players with at least 4,000 career plate appearances.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] Dunn's then-bizarre statistical profile helped pave the way for a new, statistically focused "Moneyball" style of baseball, which downplayed the negative value of strikeouts and emphasized the positive value of walks and home runs.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] Although Dunn was by no means the first TTO-focused baseball player - Babe Ruth's TTO rate was 46.1% in the 1920s - Dunn's career coincided with a league-wide rise in TTO-style baseball.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] By 2017, the leaguewide TTO rate was a record 33.5%.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] Dunn was also criticized for his at times prolonged offensive slumps.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] He admitted that "When I'm going bad, I'm the worst player in the league.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] Although Dunn's batting style was relatively unaffected by defense, he was himself one of the most woeful defenders of his era.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] He frequently surrendered hits and extra bases to opposing batters.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] When Dunn retired in 2014, Baseball Reference said that he had cost his team more wins on defense (-29.5) than any other player since 1901.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] For his career, FanGraphs calculated that Dunn accumulated 252.8 defensive runs below average, over 60 runs worse than the second-worst defender, David Ortiz, who played most of his career at designated hitter.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] Dunn's 2009 season was particularly woeful; his defense was rated at -35 runs by UZR and -43 runs by DRS.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] Because of Dunn's polarizing statistical profile, he is commonly regarded as both a poster boy for and casualty of the sabermetric movement.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] At the time, sabermetric analysis had difficulty estimating the true value of defense with any precision, and analytically minded general managers tended to undervalue defense.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] Accordingly, Dunn's $112.7 million in career earnings nearly doubled those of his White Sox teammate Juan Pierre, even though Pierre's superior defense meant that the two players had similar career wins above replacement.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] SB Nation's Graham MacAree opined that if modern analytics had been in common use at the start of Dunn's career, Dunn would have quickly become a full-time DH.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] Instead, he was allowed to spend most of his career in the National League, which did not have the DH at the time, allowing his defense to drag down his overall production.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] During his time with the Cincinnati Reds, Dunn's defensive effort was frequently questioned.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] In 2007, Reds announcer Marty Brennaman complained that "I think he was overweight last year.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] You see no energy whatsoever and that disappoints the heck out of me." (Brennaman sought to make amends with Dunn when the former was inducted into the Reds Hall of Fame in 2021.) In addition, Toronto Blue Jays general manager J.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] Ricciardi publicly insinuated that Dunn "doesn't really like baseball that much," although he later apologized for his comments.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] However, Washington Nationals general manager Mike Rizzo defended Dunn's effort, calling him "the most misunderstood player I have heard about in recent memory.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] The way he was misconstrued [in Cincinnati] was almost unbelievable.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] He'd go out there 162 games if you'd let him.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] In December 2005, Reds manager Jerry Narron informed the press that, due to the trade of popular first baseman Sean Casey to the Pittsburgh Pirates for left-handed pitcher Dave Williams, Dunn would be moving to first base for the 2006 season.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] However, with the acquisition of free agent first baseman Scott Hatteberg (who played for the Oakland Athletics in 2005) during spring training and the March 20 trade of outfielder Wily Mo Peña to the Boston Red Sox for right-handed pitcher Bronson Arroyo, the plan to convert Dunn was scrapped.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] Dunn had mentioned that he would rather not play first base.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] After Nick Johnson was traded to the Florida Marlins, Dunn was made the Washington Nationals' everyday first baseman.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] During Dunn's tenure with the Chicago White Sox, he mostly played as a designated hitter, sometimes filling in for Paul Konerko at first base in games where Konerko himself played as the DH.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adam-dunn] Dunn appeared in the 2013 film *Dallas Buyers Club* as a bartender; he is also an investor in the film.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adjusted-era] Where ERA is the pitcher's ERA, lgERA is the average ERA of the league, and PF is the park factor of the pitcher in question.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adjusted-era] The average ERA+ is set to be 100; a score above 100 indicates that the pitcher performed better than average, while below 100 indicates worse than average.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adjusted-era] For instance, imagine the average ERA in the league is 4.00: if pitcher A has an ERA of 4.00 but is pitching in a ballpark that favors hitters, his ERA+ will be over 100.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adjusted-era] Likewise, if pitcher B has an ERA of 4.00 but pitches in a ballpark favoring pitchers, then his ERA+ will be below 100.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adjusted-era] As a result, ERA+ can be used to compare pitchers across different run environments.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adjusted-era] In the above example, while ERA will lead one to believe that both pitchers pitched at the same level due to their ERAs being equivalent, ERA+ indicates that pitcher A performed better than pitcher B.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adjusted-era] ERA+ can thus be used to neutralize the effects of some well-known advantages and disadvantages on pitchers' ERA scores.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adjusted-era] Pedro Martínez holds the modern record for highest ERA+ in a single season; he posted a 1.74 ERA in the 2000 season while pitching in the American League, which had an average ERA of 4.92, which gave Martínez an ERA+ of 291.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adjusted-era] While Bob Gibson has the lowest ERA in modern times (1.12 in the National League in 1968), the average ERA was 2.99 that year (the so-called Year of the Pitcher) and so Gibson's ERA+ is 258, eighth highest since 1900.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adjusted-era] 1968 was the last year that Major League Baseball employed the use of a pitcher's mound at 15 inches (380 mm); after that season it was lowered to 10 inches (250 mm).
[src:batting-average-baseball/adjusted-era] The career record for ERA+ (with a minimum of 1,000 innings pitched) is held by Mariano Rivera, a closer whose career ERA+ is 205.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adjusted-era] Upon retirement in 2013, with an ERA+ of 194 in his final season, Rivera's career record of 205 surpassed the record among retired players of 154, held by Martínez, bumping Jim Devlin, a pitcher in the 1870s, to third with 151.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adjusted-era] Roger Clemens topped a 200 ERA+ three times, and Greg Maddux had two such seasons.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adjusted-era] Players in **bold** are active as of the end of the 2020 season and have not announced their retirement.
[src:batting-average-baseball/adjusted-era] Single-season leaders include only pitchers eligible for the ERA title (a pitcher must throw a minimum of one inning per game scheduled for his team during the season to qualify for the ERA title).
[src:batting-average-baseball/adjusted-era] Only pitchers with 1,000 or more innings pitched are shown in the career leader list.
[src:batting-average-baseball/american-league] The **American League of Professional Baseball Clubs**, known simply as the **American League** (**AL**), is the younger of two leagues constituting Major League Baseball (MLB) in the United States and Canada.
[src:batting-average-baseball/american-league] It developed from the Western League, a minor league based in the Great Lakes states, which eventually aspired to major league status.
[src:batting-average-baseball/american-league] It is sometimes called the **Junior Circuit** because it claimed Major League status for the 1901 season, 25 years after the formation of the National League (the "Senior Circuit").
[src:batting-average-baseball/american-league] Since 1903, the American League champion has played in the World Series against the National League champion with only two exceptions: 1904, when the NL champion New York Giants refused to play their AL counterpart, and 1994, when a players' strike resulted in the cancellation of the Series.
[src:batting-average-baseball/american-league] Through 2025, American League teams have won 68 of the 121 World Series played since 1903.
[src:batting-average-baseball/american-league] The New York Yankees have won 27 World Series and 41 American League titles, the most in major league history.
[src:batting-average-baseball/american-league] The Philadelphia/Kansas City/Oakland Athletics have won the second most AL titles with 15, followed by the Boston Red Sox with 14.
[src:batting-average-baseball/american-league] For decades, Major League baseball clubs only played teams from their own league during the regular season and playoffs, with only the two pennant winners meeting in the World Series.
[src:batting-average-baseball/american-league] The AL and NL also employed and trained their own umpires, who only worked regular season games in their own league.
[src:batting-average-baseball/american-league] These differences resulted in the leagues developing slightly different strategies and styles of play.
[src:batting-average-baseball/american-league] The American League was usually regarded as the less "traditional" league during the 20th century, a reputation most exemplified by the introduction of the designated hitter rule in 1973, which encouraged AL managers to largely abandon "smallball" tactics.
[src:batting-average-baseball/american-league] Though both leagues agreed to be jointly governed by a commissioner in 1920, they remained separate business entities with their own presidents and management.
[src:batting-average-baseball/american-league] This was the case until after the 1999 season, when the American League legally merged with the National League under the auspices of Major League Baseball, which now operates much like other North American professional sports leagues, albeit with two "leagues" instead of "conferences".
[src:batting-average-baseball/american-league] Originally a minor league known as the Western League, which existed from 1885 to 1899 with teams in mostly Great Lakes states, the league changed its name to the American League for the 1900 season and the next year developed into a second major league as a competitor to the older National League.
[src:batting-average-baseball/american-league] This was prompted by the NL dropping four teams following the 1899 season after having absorbed its previous rival, the American Association, which disbanded in 1891 after ten seasons.
[src:batting-average-baseball/american-league] In its early history of the late 1880s, the minor Western League struggled until 1894, when Ban Johnson became the president of the league.
[src:batting-average-baseball/american-league] Johnson pushed the league to rise to major league status, after the name change to the American League was decided in a league meeting in Milwaukee, Wisconsin, at the former Republican Hotel.
[src:batting-average-baseball/american-league] A historical marker is at the intersection of North Dr.
[src:batting-average-baseball/american-league] Drive and West Kilbourn Avenue where the hotel once stood.
[src:batting-average-baseball/american-league] In March 1904, Johnson moved the league's headquarters from Chicago to New York.
[src:batting-average-baseball/american-league] Babe Ruth, noted as one of the most prolific hitters in Major League Baseball history, spent the majority of his career in the American League with the Boston Red Sox and the New York Yankees.
[src:batting-average-baseball/american-league] From 1973 to 2022 The American League had one notable difference versus the rival National League, as it had the designated hitter rule.
[src:batting-average-baseball/american-league] Under the rule, a team may use a batter in its lineup who is not in the field defensively, replacing the pitcher in the batting order, compared to the old rule that made it mandatory for the pitcher to bat.
[src:batting-average-baseball/american-league] In the last two decades, the season schedule has allowed occasional interleague play.
[src:batting-average-baseball/american-league] In 1969, the AL (and NL) were divided into East and West divisions, with a postseason playoff series for the pennant and the right to play in the World Series.
[src:batting-average-baseball/american-league] Until the late 1970s, league umpires working behind home plate wore large, balloon-style chest protectors worn outside the shirt or coat, while their colleagues in the National League wore chest protectors inside the shirt or coat.
[src:batting-average-baseball/american-league] In 1977, new umpires (including Steve Palermo) had to wear the inside chest protector, although those on staff wearing the outside protector could continue to do so.
[src:batting-average-baseball/american-league] Most umpires made the switch to the inside protector, led by Don Denkinger in 1975 and Jim Evans the next year, although several did not, including Bill Haller, Russ Goetz, George Maloney, Bill Kunkel and Jerry Neudecker, who became the last full-time MLB umpire to use the outside protector in 1985.
[src:batting-average-baseball/american-league] In 1998, the newly franchised Tampa Bay Devil Rays joined the league, and the Arizona Diamondbacks joined the National League: i.e., each league added a fifteenth team.
[src:batting-average-baseball/american-league] An odd number of teams per league meant that at least one team in each league would have to be idle on any given day, or alternatively, that odd team out would have had to play an interleague game against its counterpart in the other league.
[src:batting-average-baseball/american-league] The initial plan was to have three five-team divisions per league with inter-league play year-round—possibly as many as 30 interleague games per team each year.
[src:batting-average-baseball/american-league] For various reasons, it soon seemed more practical to have an even number of teams in both leagues.
[src:batting-average-baseball/american-league] The Milwaukee Brewers agreed to change leagues to become the National League's 16th team, moving from the AL Central to the NL Central.
[src:batting-average-baseball/american-league] At the same time, the Detroit Tigers were moved from the AL East to the AL Central, making room for the Devil Rays in the East.
[src:batting-average-baseball/american-league] Even after expansion, the American League then continued with 14 teams.
[src:batting-average-baseball/american-league] This situation changed again in 2013 when the Houston Astros moved from the National League Central division to the American League West.
[src:batting-average-baseball/american-league] The Astros had been in the NL for 51 years since beginning as an expansion team in 1962.
[src:batting-average-baseball/american-league] Since their move, both leagues now consist of 15 teams.
[src:batting-average-baseball/american-league] For the first 96 years, American League teams faced their National League counterparts only in exhibition games or in the World Series.
[src:batting-average-baseball/american-league] Beginning in 1997, interleague games have been played during the regular season and count in the standings.
[src:batting-average-baseball/american-league] As part of the agreement instituting interleague play, the designated-hitter rule was used only in games where the American League team is the home team, until the 2022 season, when the universal DH rule was implemented.
[src:batting-average-baseball/american-league] In 2023, American League teams played 46 regular season interleague games against all 15 National League teams, 23 at home and 23 on the road.
[src:batting-average-baseball/american-league] In 2000, the American League ended its status as a legally independent entity when the American and National Leagues were both merged into the legal entity Major League Baseball (MLB).
[src:batting-average-baseball/american-league] This left MLB as a single league, divided into two parts, also called leagues.
[src:batting-average-baseball/american-league] This change in legal status had no effect on play, scheduling, and so forth.
[src:batting-average-baseball/american-league] There were eight charter teams in 1901, the league's first year as a major league, and the next year the original Milwaukee Brewers (not to be confused with the current Milwaukee Brewers) moved to St.
[src:batting-average-baseball/american-league] Louis Browns, and the year after the New York Highlanders replaced the disbanded original Baltimore Orioles.
[src:batting-average-baseball/american-league] Those eight franchises constituted the league for 52 seasons until the Browns moved to Baltimore and took up the Orioles name.
[src:batting-average-baseball/american-league] The first line is the transformation of the American League (AL) to a major league in 1901.
[src:batting-average-baseball/american-league] The second line is the beginning of the expansion era in 1961.
[src:batting-average-baseball/american-league] The third line marks the legal merger of the American and National Leagues into a single Major League Baseball in 2000.
[src:batting-average-baseball/american-league] World Series championships are shown with a "•", American League Pennants before the World Series are shown with a "#", and American League Pennants who lost the World Series are shown with a "^".
[src:batting-average-baseball/american-league] No World Series was played in 1904, so the pennant winners for each league are indicated.
[src:batting-average-baseball/american-league] Due to the 1994–95 Major League Baseball strike, there were no pennant or World Series winners in 1994, so this year is left blank.
[src:batting-average-baseball/american-league] Following the 1999 season, the American and National Leagues were merged with Major League Baseball, and the leagues ceased to exist as business entities.
[src:batting-average-baseball/american-league] The position of the American League President and National League President became honorary.
[src:batting-average-baseball/batting-average-baseball] In baseball, **batting average** (**BA**) is determined by dividing a player's hits by their total at-bats.
[src:batting-average-baseball/batting-average-baseball] It is usually rounded to three decimal places and read without the decimal: A player with a batting average of .300 is said to be "batting three hundred".
[src:batting-average-baseball/batting-average-baseball] If necessary to break ties, batting averages could be taken beyond the .001 measurement.
[src:batting-average-baseball/batting-average-baseball] In this context, .001 is considered a "point", such that a .235 batter is five points higher than a .230 batter.
[src:batting-average-baseball/batting-average-baseball] Henry Chadwick, an English statistician raised on cricket, was an influential figure in the early history of baseball.
[src:batting-average-baseball/batting-average-baseball] He is credited with creating the modern box score, in 1859, and the practice of denoting a strikeout with a "K".
[src:batting-average-baseball/batting-average-baseball] In 1869, another early baseball proponent, Alfred Wright, published an end-of-season summary that included the average number of times a batter had "clean" hits on a *per game* basis.
[src:batting-average-baseball/batting-average-baseball] In 1871, a writer for the *New York Clipper*, Hervie Dobson, proposed that a batter's "average is found by dividing his total 'times first base on clean hits' by his total number of times he went to the bat"—hits divided by at bats.
[src:batting-average-baseball/batting-average-baseball] By 1874, some teams were calculating batting averages, and by 1876, it was being calculated by all teams of the National League.
[src:batting-average-baseball/batting-average-baseball] In modern times, a season batting average of .300 or higher is considered to be excellent, and an average higher than .400 is a nearly unachievable goal.
[src:batting-average-baseball/batting-average-baseball] The last Major League Baseball (MLB) player to do so, with enough plate appearances to qualify for the batting championship, was Ted Williams of the Boston Red Sox, who hit .406 in 1941.
[src:batting-average-baseball/batting-average-baseball] Note that batting averages are rounded; entering the final day of the 1941 season, Williams was at 179-for-448, which is .39955 and would have been recorded as .400 via rounding.
[src:batting-average-baseball/batting-average-baseball] However, Williams played in both games of a doubleheader, went 6-for-8, and ended the season 185-for-456, which is .40570 and becomes .406 when rounded.
[src:batting-average-baseball/batting-average-baseball] Since 1941, no American League or National League player has hit .400 or above—the highest single-season average in those leagues has been .394 by Tony Gwynn of the San Diego Padres in 1994.
[src:batting-average-baseball/batting-average-baseball] Wade Boggs hit .401 over a 162-game span with Boston from June 9, 1985, to June 6, 1986, but never hit above .368 for an MLB season.
[src:batting-average-baseball/batting-average-baseball] There have been numerous attempts to explain the disappearance of the .400 hitter, with one of the more rigorous discussions of this question appearing in Stephen Jay Gould's 1996 book *Full House*.
[src:batting-average-baseball/batting-average-baseball] Josh Gibson hit .466 in 1943 while playing for the Homestead Grays of the Negro National League, one of several leagues within Negro league baseball that are now recognized by MLB.
[src:batting-average-baseball/batting-average-baseball] Gibson holds the record for highest major-league career batting average at .371, four points higher than Ty Cobb, who has the second-highest career average at .367.
[src:batting-average-baseball/batting-average-baseball] The record for lowest career batting average for a player with more than 2,500 at-bats belongs to Bill Bergen, a catcher who played from 1901 to 1911 and recorded a .170 average in 3,028 career at-bats.
[src:batting-average-baseball/batting-average-baseball] Hugh Duffy, who played from 1888 to 1906, is credited with the highest single-season batting average, having hit .440 in 1894.
[src:batting-average-baseball/batting-average-baseball] The modern-era (post-1900) record for highest batting average for a season is held by Nap Lajoie, who hit .426 in 1901, the first year of play for the American League.
[src:batting-average-baseball/batting-average-baseball] The modern-era record for the lowest batting average for a player that qualified for the batting title is held by Chris Davis, who hit .168 in 2018.
[src:batting-average-baseball/batting-average-baseball] While finishing six plate appearances short of qualifying for the batting title, Adam Dunn of the Chicago White Sox hit .159 for the 2011 season, nine points lower than the record.
[src:batting-average-baseball/batting-average-baseball] The highest batting average for a rookie was .408 in 1911 by Shoeless Joe Jackson.
[src:batting-average-baseball/batting-average-baseball] The league batting average in MLB for the 2018 season was .248, with the highest modern-era MLB average being .296 in 1930, and the lowest being .237 in 1968.
[src:batting-average-baseball/batting-average-baseball] For non-pitchers, a batting average below .230 is often considered poor, and one below .200 is usually unacceptable.
[src:batting-average-baseball/batting-average-baseball] This latter level is sometimes referred to as "The Mendoza Line", named for Mario Mendoza—a lifetime .215 hitter but a good defensive shortstop.
[src:batting-average-baseball/batting-average-baseball] Sabermetrics, the study of baseball statistics, considers batting average a weak measure of performance because it does not correlate as well as other measures to runs scored, thereby causing it to have little predictive value.
[src:batting-average-baseball/batting-average-baseball] Batting average does not take into account bases on balls (walks) or power, whereas other statistics such as on-base percentage and slugging percentage have been specifically designed to measure such concepts.
[src:batting-average-baseball/batting-average-baseball] Adding these statistics together form a player's on-base plus slugging or "OPS".
[src:batting-average-baseball/batting-average-baseball] This is commonly seen as a much better, though not perfect, indicator of a player's overall batting ability as it is a measure of hitting for average, hitting for power, and drawing walks.
[src:batting-average-baseball/batting-average-baseball] In rare instances, players have concluded their careers with a perfect batting average of 1.000—through the 2021 season, there were 94 such players in major-league history, 83 of whom recorded exactly one hit in one at bat.
[src:batting-average-baseball/batting-average-baseball] Only one player with a 1.000 average has had three hits—outfielder John Paciorek (1963), who had three hits in three at bats; he also had two walks, and scored four runs.
[src:batting-average-baseball/batting-average-baseball] Players who had two hits in their only two at bats include: pitcher Frank O'Connor (1893), catcher Mike Hopkins (1902), pitcher Doc Tonkin (1907), pitcher Hal Deviney (1920), pitcher Fred Schemanske (1923), pitcher Chet Kehn (1942), second baseman Steve Biras (1944), and pitcher Jason Roach (2003).
[src:batting-average-baseball/batting-average-baseball] Pitcher Esteban Yan, who played in 472 major-league games from 1996 to 2006, mainly in the American League (where pitchers have rarely batted since the introduction of the designated hitter in 1973), also had two hits in his only two at bats, one a home run.
[src:batting-average-baseball/batting-average-baseball] The MLB batting averages championships (often referred to as "the batting title") are awarded annually to the player in each league with the highest batting average.
[src:batting-average-baseball/batting-average-baseball] Ty Cobb holds the MLB and American League (AL) record for most batting titles, officially winning 11 in his career.
[src:batting-average-baseball/batting-average-baseball] The National League (NL) record of eight batting titles is shared by Honus Wagner and Tony Gwynn.
[src:batting-average-baseball/batting-average-baseball] This is officially Rule 10.22(a), but it is also known as the "Tony Gwynn rule" because the Padres' player won the batting crown in 1996 with a .353 average on just 498 plate appearances (i.e., he was four short).
[src:batting-average-baseball/batting-average-baseball] Gwynn was awarded the title since he would have led the league even if he had gone 0-for-4 in those missing plate appearances.
[src:batting-average-baseball/batting-average-baseball] His average would have dropped to .349, five points better than second-place Ellis Burks' .344.
[src:batting-average-baseball/batting-average-baseball] In 2012, a one-time amendment to the rule was made to disqualify Melky Cabrera from the title.
[src:batting-average-baseball/batting-average-baseball] Cabrera requested that he be disqualified after serving a suspension that season for a positive testosterone test.
[src:batting-average-baseball/batting-average-baseball] He had batted .346 with 501 plate appearances, and the original rule would have awarded him the title over San Francisco Giants teammate Buster Posey, who won batting .336.
[src:batting-average-baseball/batting-average-baseball] The highest recorded single-season batting average in Minor League Baseball is .462, accomplished by Gary Redus in 1978, when he played for the Billings Mustangs, an affiliate of the Cincinnati Reds in the Rookie Advanced-level Pioneer League.
[src:batting-average-baseball/batting-average-baseball] Redus was 117-for-253 in 68 games, as the Pioneer League only plays from June to early September.
[src:batting-average-baseball/batting-average-baseball] Redus went on to play in MLB from 1982 through 1994, batting .252 during his MLB career.
[src:batting-average-baseball/batting-average-baseball] In Nippon Professional Baseball (NPB), the leader in career batting average is Isao Harimoto, a member of the Japanese Baseball Hall of Fame, who hit .319 in his NPB career.
[src:batting-average-baseball/batting-average-baseball] Ichiro Suzuki batted .353 in NPB, but does not have enough NPB career at-bats to qualify for the league's title.
[src:batting-average-baseball/batting-average-baseball] Sadaharu Oh had a batting average of .355 in 1973 season.
[src:batting-average-baseball/batting-average-baseball] Randy Bass had a batting average of .389 in 1986 season.
[src:batting-average-baseball/batting-average-baseball] In KBO League (KBO), the leader in career batting average is Jung-hoo Lee, who hit .340 in his KBO career and is currently an active player.
[src:batting-average-baseball/batting-average-baseball] Baek In-chun had a batting average of .412 in 1982 season.
[src:batting-average-baseball/batting-average-baseball] This is the highest batting average of one season in KBO League.
